<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,464]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,151,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Bionomics</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[342,449,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,193,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1433,193,1924]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 7. Stigmella apicibrunella Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov. 2 — habitat, western slopes of the equatorial Andes (Ecuador: Chimborazo Province) at altitudes about 1800 m; 3 — host plant Acalypha padifolia Kunth (Euphorbiaceae); 4, leafmines; 5 – 7, female paratype adults." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583343/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figs 2–4</figureCitation>
). Host-plant: 
<taxonomicName authority="Kunth" authorityName="Kunth" box="[610,909,151,176]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Acalypha" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="padifolia">
<emphasis box="[610,827,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Acalypha padifolia</emphasis>
Kunth
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[927,1097,151,176]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Euphorbiaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation box="[1125,1197,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,193,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1433,193,1924]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 7. Stigmella apicibrunella Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov. 2 — habitat, western slopes of the equatorial Andes (Ecuador: Chimborazo Province) at altitudes about 1800 m; 3 — host plant Acalypha padifolia Kunth (Euphorbiaceae); 4, leafmines; 5 – 7, female paratype adults." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583343/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Larva yellow with brown head; mines in leaves in January and, judging by observed numerous old (empty) leaf-mines, also in December. Leaf-mine (
<figureCitation box="[415,484,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,193,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1433,193,1924]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 7. Stigmella apicibrunella Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov. 2 — habitat, western slopes of the equatorial Andes (Ecuador: Chimborazo Province) at altitudes about 1800 m; 3 — host plant Acalypha padifolia Kunth (Euphorbiaceae); 4, leafmines; 5 – 7, female paratype adults." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583343/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) starts as a very slender sinuous gallery with a very wide line of black or blackish brown frass. Larval exit slit on upper side of the leaf. Cocoon very pale, yellowish beige; length 
<quantity box="[1291,1432,260,284]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="2.2" valueMax="2.3" valueMin="2.1">2.1–2.3 mm</quantity>
, maximum width 
<quantity box="[342,410,296,320]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
. Adults fly in February.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,464]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,332,357]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[367,444,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1986,2008]" captionTargetBox="[182,1401,510,1932]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1401,509,1961]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distribution map to the species treated in the current paper." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583342/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figs 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[465,482,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,193,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1433,193,1924]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 7. Stigmella apicibrunella Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov. 2 — habitat, western slopes of the equatorial Andes (Ecuador: Chimborazo Province) at altitudes about 1800 m; 3 — host plant Acalypha padifolia Kunth (Euphorbiaceae); 4, leafmines; 5 – 7, female paratype adults." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583343/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">2</figureCitation>
). This species occurs on the western slopes of the equatorial Andes (
<collectingCountry box="[1333,1432,332,357]" name="Ecuador" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion box="[151,397,367,392]" country="Ecuador" name="Chimborazo" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Chimborazo Province</collectingRegion>
